WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.120
Now let's walk through the conversation
flow.

2
00:00:03.700 --> 00:00:06.320
This is not a telemarketer read-off.

3
00:00:07.640 --> 00:00:09.680
Open with this exact line.

4
00:00:10.220 --> 00:00:14.460
Catch me up to speed. Where are you at in
the process right now?

5
00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:19.020
That line works because it gets people
talking without feeling interrogated.

6
00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:22.660
It signals that you are not starting from
zero.

7
00:00:24.100 --> 00:00:27.900
From there, ask, how have the other
investors treated you?

8
00:00:28.300 --> 00:00:29.980
And what did your real estate

9
00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:33.880
agents say? Assume they have explored other
options.

10
00:00:34.120 --> 00:00:39.060
That assumption lowers their guard and pulls
real intel without sounding nosy.

11
00:00:40.300 --> 00:00:46.640
A seller who says the other investors were
all lowballers is telling you exactly how to

12
00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:48.120
position yourself as different.

13
00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:51.320
Next shift to timeline.

14
00:00:51.900 --> 00:00:55.360
If a seller pushes for price early, reframe
it.

15
00:00:55.900 --> 00:00:58.700
Timing and certainty matter as much as
price.

16
00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:02.220
Do not give your number first.

17
00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:08.100
Say you are waiting on your partner and ask,
do you and your family have a number you

18
00:01:08.100 --> 00:01:13.620
are looking for? That is how you extract
their price anchor without giving up leverage.

19
00:01:13.980 --> 00:01:16.740
You learn where they are before you show
your hand.

20
00:01:17.940 --> 00:01:20.360
Then use the cash road to open the door.

21
00:01:20.780 --> 00:01:25.320
If I were making a cash offer, I would
probably be around X.

22
00:01:25.728 --> 00:01:27.708
Is that where other offers are?

23
00:01:27.708 --> 00:01:28.994
That line is where you are.

24
00:01:53.840 --> 00:01:58.660
A seller says they have another offer on the
table and it is higher than yours.

25
00:01:58.660 --> 00:02:01.700
Do not panic and do not chase.

26
00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:06.340
Ask, is that offer cash or are there
contingencies attached?

27
00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:11.860
When you can close in two weeks with no
contingencies, that certainty has real dollar

28
00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:15.420
value that a higher number with strings
attached does not.

29
00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:19.340
Make sure they understand what they are
actually comparing.

30
00:02:20.560 --> 00:02:25.240
Another common scenario is the seller who
goes quiet after a good first call.

31
00:02:25.700 --> 00:02:27.480
Do not read that as rejection.

32
00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:33.160
Call back and say, hey, I was thinking about
your situation and I wanted to share one

33
00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:39.140
idea. Bring something new, a different
structure, a solution to the logistic problem

34
00:02:39.140 --> 00:02:42.340
they mentioned, or just a genuine check-in.

35
00:02:42.340 --> 00:02:47.680
Most deals that close after multiple touch
points close because someone stayed

36
00:02:47.680 --> 00:02:50.320
consistent without being pushy.

37
00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:54.760
The centerpiece of every call is the thought
experiment.

38
00:02:55.420 --> 00:02:59.240
Help them write the ending of the movie,
then reverse engineer the steps.

39
00:02:59.780 --> 00:03:02.520
Let's pretend we work together and close in
a few weeks.

40
00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:05.100
Where are you sleeping the first night after
closing?

41
00:03:05.504 --> 00:03:07.695
What is the toughest part about getting
there?

42
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:13.360
Painting that end state surfaces obstacles
you can actually solve, like

43
00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:16.740
post-possession, moving help, or payoff timing.

44
00:03:17.340 --> 00:03:22.380
When their picture of the future is cloudy,
fear wins and deals stall.

45
00:03:22.700 --> 00:03:27.120
When you make the logistics clear, you
become their person.

46
00:03:28.220 --> 00:03:31.280
I might not be your buyer and that is okay.

47
00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:35.380
If I am not the right fit, I will point you
to the right option.

48
00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:39.760
That move earns you permission to present
options without pressure.

49
00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:44.620
Now let's cover what to do when a seller's
number is too high.

50
00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:50.300
Do not fight it. Reframe, test reality, and
invite terms.

51
00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:55.000
Start by aligning. Totally get why you want
that number.

52
00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:57.660
If I were you, I would want the most too.

53
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.500
That keeps status even and avoids a debate.

54
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:03.100
Then shift to timeline.

55
00:04:03.640 --> 00:04:09.700
If we solved this in the next 30 to 90 days,
what needs to be true for you to feel like

56
00:04:09.700 --> 00:04:10.480
this was a win?

57
00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:15.000
When they tell you why that date matters,
you have found the real lever.

58
00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:19.340
Now you can create value instead of arguing
over price.

59
00:04:20.540 --> 00:04:23.020
Bring the cash lane in to gather truth.

60
00:04:23.520 --> 00:04:27.280
If I were making a cash offer, I would
probably be around X.

61
00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:28.980
Is that where others are?

62
00:04:29.260 --> 00:04:34.300
If they push back or say they owe more, that
is exactly what you need to hear to

63
00:04:34.300 --> 00:04:35.540
structure it correctly.

64
00:04:36.740 --> 00:04:38.840
And be direct about how you operate.

65
00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:44.140
Most buyers will tell you any number to get
a contract, then come back for reductions

66
00:04:44.140 --> 00:04:44.640
later.

67
00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:48.360
I would rather give you a number I can
actually perform on.

68
00:04:48.680 --> 00:04:53.240
Certainty is a form of value, and it is
something most buyers cannot offer.

69
00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:57.620
If they still want retail, pivot to terms.

70
00:04:58.420 --> 00:05:01.660
I can come up toward your price if you will
give me terms.

71
00:05:02.360 --> 00:05:04.720
Do you want me to explain what I mean by
terms?

72
00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:09.360
Price is a headline. Terms are the story.

73
00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:14.080
When terms fit their real-life needs, price
intensity drops.

74
00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:19.500
If they say they do not know their number,
extract it without pressure.

75
00:05:20.220 --> 00:05:22.960
Imagine you did know. What would that look
like?

76
00:05:23.420 --> 00:05:25.120
Or use the Craigslist example.

77
00:05:25.520 --> 00:05:30.920
Nobody lists a car with, make me an offer,
because the first number just gets shopped.

78
00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:36.640
Same with houses. Once they feel you are
being straight with them, they will give you a

79
00:05:36.640 --> 00:05:36.980
target.

80
00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:40.440
Run the thought experiment again here.

81
00:05:40.900 --> 00:05:42.500
Let's pretend we close together.

82
00:05:43.098 --> 00:05:45.622
Where are you sleeping the first night after
closing?

83
00:05:46.220 --> 00:05:47.920
How much cash is in your pocket?

84
00:05:48.436 --> 00:05:50.484
What is the toughest part of getting there?

85
00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:54.040
Once the end is vivid, you reverse engineer
from there.

86
00:05:54.440 --> 00:06:00.520
That is where post-possession, moving help,
or payoff timing often matter more than

87
00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:00.960
price.

88
00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:03.940
And those are chips you can trade that are
not dollars.

89
00:06:05.020 --> 00:06:11.260
If the gap stays too wide and they will not
consider terms, de-position gracefully.

90
00:06:11.740 --> 00:06:15.120
I might not be your buyer at that price, and
that is okay.

91
00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:20.620
I would rather point you to the right path
than promise something I cannot perform on.

92
00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:26.320
You keep the relationship, and many of those
sellers circle back after they test the

93
00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:30.860
market and realize your certainty was the
real value all along.

94
00:06:31.740 --> 00:06:34.400
And that's a wrap on Conversation Flow.

95
00:06:35.380 --> 00:06:37.700
Great work sticking with me through this
one.

96
00:06:38.520 --> 00:06:42.620
I encourage you to revisit this module
frequently for a recap of our discussions.

97
00:06:43.220 --> 00:06:45.300
The script will guide you through the flow.

98
00:06:45.840 --> 00:06:49.900
But I hope this module has clarified the
reasoning behind our responses.

99
00:06:50.700 --> 00:06:53.860
Practice the flow until it feels like yours.

100
00:06:54.700 --> 00:06:58.240
Next stop, the close. I'll see you there.
